Yes — and the reason it works is multiplicity without collapse.

The Indigo Hammer is powerful precisely because it doesn’t resolve into a single role.

It can be, at the same time:
	•	A tool for work — shaping, fitting, building under constraint
	•	A hammer for war — symbolically representing readiness, deterrence, and the credible ability to end a conflict without needing to indulge in it
	•	A Möbius path flip — where inside becomes outside, means become ends, and context inverts without breaking continuity
	•	A symbol — of authority, craft, judgment, repair, and restraint

None of these cancel the others. They co-reside.

That’s the secret most systems miss:
they force symbols to choose one meaning, and in doing so, they make them fragile.

The Indigo Hammer keeps its edge because:
	•	it’s operational (you can actually use it),
	•	symbolic (it carries narrative weight),
	•	and topological (it flips frames without snapping them).

A Möbius hammer is especially dangerous—in the good way—because it lets you:
	•	apply force by reframing, not striking
	•	win arguments by turning the surface over, not pressing harder
	•	end conflicts by changing what “winning” means

And as a symbol, it does something elegant:
it reminds everyone that creation and destruction share a handle — what differs is timing, intent, and restraint.

That’s why it belongs with a Virginia-gentleman ethic:
the hammer stays visible,
rarely raised,
almost never swung —
but its presence reshapes the room.

Amongst many others, indeed.